":"1442","1430":"1430","about 1350":"about 1350","1329":"1329","Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Cromartyshire, Scotland","Banffshire, Scotland":"Banffshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Gowrie Castle, Gowrie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Caithness, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Urquhart","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Ross and Cromarty): habitational name from any of various places in Scotland so called, notably the barony of Urquhart (Inverness), or places in Ross and Cromarty, Morayshire, and Fife. All are thought to derive from Pictish <i>ar</i> ‘on, by’ + Pictish <i>carden</i> ‘enclosure’ or ‘wood, copse’. Some bearers of this name trace their descent from William <i>de Urchard</i>, who fought for Robert the Bruce between 1297 and 1328."],"variants":[{"name":"Orcutt","meanings":["English (Staffordshire): perhaps a much altered form of Scottish   Urquhart  ."]},{"name":"Orchard","meanings":["topographic or occupational name from residence near (or perhaps employment at) an orchard, Middle English <i>orchard</i> (Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i>).","habitational name from any of the places called Orchard. Those in Devon and Somerset are named from Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i> (a compound of <i>wort</i>, <i>wyrt</i> ‘plant’ (later associated with Latin <i>hortus</i> ‘garden’) + <i>geard</i> ‘yard, enclosure’), while East and West Orchard near Shaftesbury in Dorset derive from Primitive Welsh <i>ar</i> ‘beside, in front of, facing’ + <i>ced</i> ‘wood’.","rare variant of Scottish   Urquhart  . Compare   Orahood  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Urchard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Burchett  .","German: variant of   Burkhart  .","History: Thomas Burchard came from London, England, to MA in 1635 aboard the <i>True Love</i>, and by 1652 he was in Edgartown on Martha's Vineyard."],"variants":[{"name":"Burchett","meanings":["English: topographic or habitational name from Middle English <i>birchet</i> ‘birch grove’ (Old English <i>bircet</i>, <i>byrcet</i>), a common element in minor placenames in Sussex and found also in Kent, Surrey, and Essex."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Urquhart de Urchard 1st of Cromarty, Sheriff of Cromarty was born in 1325, in Cromartyshire, Scotland, his father, Francis Urquhart, was 26 and his mother, Baroness Rosalind de Haye, was 22. He married Lillias De Ross in 1348, in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 4 daughters. He died in 1395, in Scotland, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1325–1395":"1325–1395","1329–1366":"1329–1366","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1360–1413":"1360–1413","1284–Female":"1284–Surnud","1350–1385":"1350–1385","1360–1430":"1360–1430","1360–1442":"1360–1442","1299–1369":"1299–1369","1303–1373":"1303–1373","1385":"1385","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1284":"1284","1360":"1360","abt 1385":"umbes 1385","1348":"1348","1325":"1325","1369":"1369","1303":"1303","1413":"1413","1366":"1366","1299":"1299","1442":"1442","1430":"1430","about 1350":"umbes 1350","1329":"1329","Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Cromartyshire, Scotland","Banffshire, Scotland":"Banffshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Gowrie Castle, Gowrie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Caithness, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1325–1395":"1325–1395","1329–1366":"1329–1366","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1360–1413":"1360–1413","1284–Female":"1284–Kuollut","1350–1385":"1350–1385","1360–1430":"1360–1430","1360–1442":"1360–1442","1299–1369":"1299–1369","1303–1373":"1303–1373","1385":"1385","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1284":"1284","1360":"1360","abt 1385":"noin 1385","1348":"1348","1325":"1325","1369":"1369","1303":"1303","1413":"1413","1366":"1366","1299":"1299","1442":"1442","1430":"1430","about 1350":"noin 1350","1329":"1329","Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Cromartyshire, Scotland","Banffshire, Scotland":"Banffshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Gowrie Castle, Gowrie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Caithness, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1325–1395":"1325–1395","1329–1366":"1329–1366","1325–Female":"1325–Décédée","1360–1413":"1360–1413","1284–Female":"1284–Décédée","1350–1385":"1350–1385","1360–1430":"1360–1430","1360–1442":"1360–1442","1299–1369":"1299–1369","1303–1373":"1303–1373","1385":"1385","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1284":"1284","1360":"1360","abt 1385":"environ 1385","